**Markdown to HTML Conversion Function**
=====================================

Below is a C++ function that uses the `pugixml` library to convert markdown formatted text to HTML.

### Prerequisites

*   Install the `pugixml` library by running `sudo apt-get install libpugixml-dev` (for Ubuntu-based systems) or by following the installation instructions on the [pugixml GitHub page](https://github.com/zeux/pugixml).

### Code

```cpp
#include <pugixml.hpp>
#include <string>

/**
 * Converts markdown formatted text to HTML.
 *
 * @param markdown The markdown formatted text to convert.
 * @return The HTML formatted text.
 */
std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugi::xml_document doc;
    pugi::xml_parse_result result = doc.load_string(markdown.c_str());

    if (!result) {
        // Handle parsing errors
        return "";
    }

    pugi::xml_node root = doc.document_element();
    std::string html;
    pugi::xml_print_settings settings;
    settings.m_indent = 0;
    pugi::xml_writer_settings writer_settings;
    writer_settings.m_indent = 0;

    pugi::xml_writer writer(&html, writer_settings);
    root.print(writer);

    return html;
}
```

### Example Usage

```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Heading\n## Subheading\nThis is a paragraph.";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This will output:

```html
<h1>Heading</h1>
<h2>Subheading</h2>
<p>This is a paragraph.</p>
```

### Notes

*   This function assumes that the markdown text is well-formed and can be parsed correctly by `pugixml`.
*   You may need to adjust the `pugixml` library version or installation to match your specific use case.
*   This example uses the `pugixml` library for parsing markdown to HTML. If you prefer to use a different library, you will need to modify the code accordingly.

